¬†@MartimusEins¬† Nothing is for everyone. That's one of the things that made Dark Souls special. And I don't see the requirement to search for things to be a chore, but instead as a means of earning your reward. 

Buying the White Sign Soapstone from an NPC in Dark Souls III's Firelink was incredibly underwhelming. Picking the Furled Finger up after 20 seconds of walking from the start of Elden Ring was even more underwhelming.

I also don't think you should ever start a Souls game with co-op. You become overly reliant on the other player, and by the time you have to do things yourself; you realize you're vastly under prepared in terms of both gear and knowledge.

I would consider myself rather experienced with these games. But I'm still struggling to tackle/ actually finish Elden Ring (and DS2 for that matter), because they seem like such a big commitment.
